# Utility Functions

Files in `src/utils/` must export utilities as `const` arrow functions.

## Types

Prefer `type` (not `interface`) for function argument objects, return shapes, and other types defined in util modules. See [typescript](typescript.mdc).

- ✅ Good:

  ```typescript
  type SlugifyOptions = { lowercase?: boolean }

  export const slugify = (input: string, options?: SlugifyOptions) => {
  ```

## Function shape

- ✅ Good:

  ```typescript
  export const slugify = (input: string) => {
    const normalized = normalizeString(input)
    if (!normalized) return ''

    return normalized
      .replace(/[^a-z0-9]+/g, '-')
      .replace(/-+/g, '-')
      .replace(/^-+|-+$/g, '')
  }

  export const groupBy = <T, K>(array: T[], keyFn: (item: T) => K): Record<string, T[]> =>
    array.reduce<Record<string, T[]>>((groups, item) => {
      const key = String(keyFn(item))
      const existingGroup = groups[key] ?? []

      return { ...groups, [key]: [...existingGroup, item] }
    }, {})
  ```

- ❌ Bad:

  ```typescript
  export function slugify(input: string) {
    return input.toLowerCase()
  }

  export default function groupBy() {}
  ```

This rule applies to utility modules only. React components and hooks follow their own conventions.
